INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (1,0,21,'2015-03-20 07:20:00','<p>test1<br></p>','test','test.html','test2','test3',NULL,'2015-03-20 19:20:42','post','published',1),(2,1,21,'2015-03-20 07:20:00','<p>test1<br></p>','test','test.html','test2','test3',NULL,'2015-03-20 19:20:42','post','inherit',0),(3,0,21,'2015-04-30 05:03:00','<p>\r\nIs your head swimming after hearing about the\r\n<a href=\"http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2015/02/finding-more-mobile-friendly-search.html\" target=\"_blank\">Google algorithm changes</a> that were recently implemented on April 21st? You are\r\nnot alone. The changes have affected thousands of small business owners, many\r\nof whom were unaware that these changes were even on the horizon. If you are\r\nquestioning what exactly these updates mean, and more concretely, how they will\r\naffect you and your small business, read on.</p><p></p>\r\n<p>The way that Google now ranks websites in the\r\nsearch results that appear on mobile devices, such as smart phones and tablets,\r\njust received a major overhaul. Have you already observed a discernable difference\r\nin your search engine rankings? These algorithm modifications would be the\r\nreason. This update does mean massive implications for small business websites,\r\nbut fortunately we are here to help you understand these changes and to use\r\nthem to your advantage.</p>\r\n<p><b>Why are These Changes Being Made?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>An ever-increasing number of people are turning\r\nto their portable devices for internet browsing, and this fact does not escape\r\nGoogle. Therefore, when a mobile user is searching on their phone, it is not\r\nbeneficial to have websites show up in the search rankings that will not load\r\nproperly when they then proceed to view them. Makes sense, right? With the\r\nrecent modifications, websites that are not fully optimized for mobile use are\r\nbeing penalized and will now show up lower in mobile search engine rankings.\r\nPlease note, that this is not affecting desktop search results.</p>\r\n<p><b>What Do These Changes Mean for Small Businesses?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When a company has not taken the steps to ensure\r\nthat their website is smartphone or tablet user-friendly, they will take a hit\r\nwhen it comes to search engine rankings. It is expected that small businesses\r\nwill suffer the most from this change when it comes to a decrease in website\r\ntraffic. A large percentage of small business owners simply do not even know\r\nthat this change has taken place, and are left wondering why their search\r\nengine rankings have suddenly dropped. Also, it is increasingly common for\r\nphysical traffic to small businesses, such as restaurants, to be due to\r\ncustomers discovering them through a last-minute search on their phone. The\r\nplus side of this development is that if a small business can create a smooth,\r\nmobile-friendly site, they will have a much better chance of winning the\r\nsearch-engine rankings game.</p>\r\n<p><b>How Do You Know if Your Website is Mobile\r\nFriendly?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Several websites that use pre-designed\r\ntemplates, may already have a website that is optimized for mobile use. So,\r\ngood news! You might be in the clear without even knowing it! If you are unsure\r\nof the quality of your website\'s conversion capabilities, Google has provided a\r\nway for businesses to test to see if their site will meet the requirements. You\r\ncan clickity-click on the following link, and enter your web address to check\r\nand see how your site measures up:</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/mobile-friendly/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/mobile-friendly/</a></p>\r\n<p>How did you do? You should be on the receiving\r\nend of an almost instantaneous answer as to whether your site is good-to-go, or\r\nwhether it might demand some updates. If your site does not pass, then you\r\nshould be provided with a few explanations that will help you on your way to\r\nupdating your site. Common issues include \"text too small to read\" or\r\n\"mobile viewport not set.\"</p>\r\n<p><b>What Can I Do to Optimize My Site and Improve My\r\nRankings?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Optimizing a website for mobile viewing rarely\r\ninvolves an entire overhaul. When developing a mobile site, there are a few\r\nsimple methods for ensuring that your results measure up. Choose the option\r\nthat works best for you.</p>\r\n<p><b>Option 1: Responsive Design</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A website featuring responsive design is a\r\npopular choice nowadays. With responsive design, your site content is\r\nessentially the same for the mobile and desktop version (same HTML). Depending\r\non the device that is being used, the layout will be tailored so that it is\r\ncomfortable to read and straightforward to navigate. Screen size and\r\norientation are both accounted for and your display will shrink or expand\r\naccordingly. With this option, all of the changes take place behind the scenes,\r\nand the user will always navigate to the same URL regardless of whether they\r\nare using a desktop computer, a smartphone or a tablet. Google prefers a\r\nwebsite with responsive design.</p>\r\n<p><b>Option 2: Separate Mobile Website</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have you ever visited a website on your phone\r\nbefore and noticed an automatic redirect to a URL with \" /mobile\", or\r\nsomething similar, following the web address? The businesses whose websites\r\ndisplay in this manner from a mobile-device have built a separate website\r\nspecifically for mobile users. When web browsing on-the-go was first gaining\r\npopularity, a separate mobile website is how most businesses handled the issue.\r\nNow, this method is considered to be one of the least efficient approaches, as\r\nit requires unnecessarily keeping up with and maintaining two separate sites.\r\nThe success of this particular method relies on the proper recognition of the\r\ndevice being used, and since new, cutting-edge yet unfamiliar technology is\r\nconstantly being released, redirects and errors are commonplace.</p>\r\n<p><b>Option 3: Dynamic Serving</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>With dynamic serving, the server will\r\nreconstruct the HTML code based on the type of device it determines is seeking\r\nto gain access to your site. As with Responsive Design, you will be able to use\r\nthe same URL as the desktop version of your site. Unlike Responsive Design,\r\nyour website content will not be a miniature version of the desktop site - it\r\nwill have it\'s own unique content that is specifically catered to a mobile\r\nuser.</p>\r\n<p>There are pros and cons to each of these\r\noptions, and it is essential to weigh the individual needs of your business\r\nbefore making a decision. If taking care of any of these changes yourself feels\r\noverwhelming, you are not alone. Fortunately, there are those of us who enjoy\r\nthis challenge and WebVision is here to help, whether it is advisement you\r\nseek or a total redesign from the ground up.<br></p><span></span><p></p>\r\n','Everything You Need to Know About the Recent Google Algorithm Changes and Your Small Business','everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-recent-google-algorithm-changes-and-your-small-business.html',NULL,'Is your head swimming after hearing about the Google algorithm changes that were recently implemented on April 21st? You are not alone. ','http://cms.gowebvision.com/media/3/img/550ceb52c3d994b55890b8bdfed0e096.jpg','2015-04-30 22:11:29','post','published',1),(4,3,21,'2015-04-30 05:03:00','<p>\r\n<p>Is your head swimming after hearing about the\r\nGoogle algorithm changes that were recently implemented on April 21st? You are\r\nnot alone. The changes have affected thousands of small business owners, many\r\nof whom were unaware that these changes were even on the horizon. If you are\r\nquestioning what exactly these updates mean, and more concretely, how they will\r\naffect you and your small business, read on.</p>\r\n<p>